374 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aquaman_2018|title=Aquaman (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| 55 (49 critics)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/aquaman|title=Aquaman reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 23, 2018}}</ref>\n| {{sort grade|A\u2212}}\n|-\n|''Shazam!''\n|91% (378 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=Shazam! (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shazam|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|71 (52 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=Shazam!|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/shazam!|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{sort grade|A}}\n|-\n|''Joker''\n|69% (524 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/joker_2019|title=Joker (2019)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|accessdate=December 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|59 (58 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/joker|title=Joker reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{sort grade|B+}}\n|-\n| ''Birds of Prey''\n|79% (342 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=Birds of Prey (And the Fantabulous Emancipation of One Harley Quinn) (2020)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/birds_of_prey_2020|access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|60 (59 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=Birds of Prey (And the Fantabulous Emancipation of One Harley Quinn)|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/birds-of-prey-and-the-fantabulous-emancipation-of-one-harley-quinn|access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|B+\n|-\n!Average\n! 67%\n! 57\n! B+\n|}\n\n== Digital distribution ==\nDC Comics are available in digital form through several sources.\n\nFree services: In 2015, [[Hoopla (digital media service)|Hoopla Digital]] became the first library-based digital system to distribute DC Comics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/06/25/hoopla-dc-comics/|title=Public library app Hoopla adds DC comics to its lineup|website=Engadget|access-date=April 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091116/https://www.engadget.com/2015/06/25/hoopla-dc-comics/|archive-date=April 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPaid services: [[Google Play]], [[ComiXology]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/10/08/dc-comics-and-vertigo-google-play/|title=DC Comics and Vertigo graphic novels arrive on Google Play, Sandman and all|website=Engadget|access-date=April 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421091118/https://www.engadget.com/2013/10/08/dc-comics-and-vertigo-google-play/|archive-date=April 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Comics|New York City|Companies}}\n{{Wikipedia books|DC Comics}}\n* Batman Day (September 17)\n* [[DC Cosmic Cards]]\n* [[DC Collectibles]]\n* [[List of DC Comics characters]]\n* [[List of comics characters which originated in other media]]\n* [[List of current DC Comics publications]]\n* [[List of films based on DC Comics]]\n* [[List of television series based on DC Comics]]\n* [[List of video games based on DC Comics]]\n* [[Publication history of DC Comics crossover events]]\n* [[List of unproduced DC Comics projects]]\n*[[DC Films]]\n*\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Goulart |first=Ron |authorlink=Ron Goulart |title=Ron Goulart's Great History of Comics Books |publisher=Contemporary Press |location=Chicago |year=1986 |isbn=0-8092-5045-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Gerard Jones |last=Jones |first=Gerard |title=Men of Tomorrow: Geeks, Gangsters, and the Birth of the Comic Book |url=https://archive.org/details/menoftomorrowgee0000jone |url-access=registration |publisher=Basic Books |year=2004 |isbn=0-465-03657-0 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q2924461|c=category:DC Comics|wikt=Appendix:DC Comics|n=Category:Comics|v=no|b=no|s=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n* [https://www.dccomics.com Dc Comics Official website]\n* {{gcdb publisher|id=54|title=DC Comics}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=publisher|id=1}}\n* [http://www.dcindexes.com Mike's Amazing World of DC Comics]\n* [http://dc.wikia.com DC Comics Database at Wikia.com]\n{{Timeline\n|before= \u2013\n|title= [[Timeline of DC Comics]] ([[Timeline of DC Comics (1930s)|1930s]])\n|years= Autumn 1934 (See also: [[National Comics Publications]])\n|after= ''New Fun Comics'', later retitled ''More Fun Comics'' series debuts. See [[More Fun Comics]] for more info and next timeline. \u2192}}\n{{Comic book publishers in North America}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{DC Comics imprints}}\n{{DC Comics War Titles}}\n{{DC events}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:DC Comics| ]]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1934]]\n[[Category:WarnerMedia brands]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. divisions]]\n[[Category:Comic book publishing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1934]]\n", "name_user": "WildStar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup, removed access-date for non-existent URL.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DC_Comics"}
{"title_page": "Bacon's Rebellion", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|1676 Virginia rebellion against the colonial government}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| latitude = \n| longitude = \n|image = Howard Pyle - The Burning of Jamestown.jpg\n|image_upright = 1.2\n|caption = ''The Burning of Jamestown'' by [[Howard Pyle]], c. 1905\n|date = 1676\n|place = [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]], [[Colony of Virginia]]\n| coordinates = <!-- type:landmark_region:US-VA -->\n| goals   = Change in Virginia's Indian-Frontier policy\n| methods = [[Demonstration (people)|Demonstrations]], [[vigilantes]]\n| status  = \n| result  = \n| concessions =\n| side1= [[Indentured servants|Common indentured servants]] and [[African-Americans|Enslaved Africans]]\n| side2= [[William Berkeley (governor)|Sir William Berkeley]], [[Colonial Governor of Virginia|Royal Colonial Governor]] appointed by the crown.\n| leadfigures1= [[Nathaniel Bacon (Virginia)|Nathaniel Bacon]] and\n [[John Ingram (Member of Bacon's Rebellion)|John Ingram]] \n| leadfigures2= [[William Berkeley (governor)|William Berkeley]]\n| casualties2= None\n| casualties1= '''Deaths''': 23 hanged<ref name=\"Geiter\" />\n| howmany2= 200\n| howmany1= 300\u2013500\n}}\n'''Bacon's Rebellion''' was an armed rebellion that took place 1676-1677 by [[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]] settlers led by [[Nathaniel Bacon (Virginia)|Nathaniel Bacon]] against the rule of Governor [[William Berkeley (governor)|William Berkeley]]. His grievances against the governor stemmed from Berkeley's dismissive policy to the political challenges of its western frontier, particularly leaving Bacon out of his inner circle and refusing to allow Bacon to take part in fur trading with [[Native American tribes in Virginia|Native Americans]], and Berkeley refusing Bacon a military commission that would allow him to fight and attack Native Americans at his own discretion. Attacks by the [[Doeg people]] are credited with inciting the popular uprising against Berkeley for failing to address the demands of the colonists regarding the safety of the frontier. The Doeg people had both traded and made war on the Virginia frontier.\n\nStarting in the 1650s, as English colonists began to settle the Northern Neck frontier, then known as Chicacoan (Secocowon), some Doeg, Patawomeck and Rappahannock began moving into the region as well and joined local tribes in disputing the settlers' claims to land and resources. In July 1666, the colonists declared war on them. By 1669, colonists had patented the land on the west of the Potomac as far north as My Lord's Island. By 1670, they had driven most of the Doeg out of the Virginia colony and into Maryland\u2014apart from those living beside the Nanzatico/Portobago in Caroline County, Virginia.\n\nThe English continued to harass the Doeg on the Northern Neck and in July 1675, a Doeg raiding party crossed the Potomac and stole hogs from Thomas Mathew, in retaliation for him not paying them for traded goods. Mathew and other colonists pursued them to Maryland and killed a group of Doeg, as well as innocent Susquehannock. A Doeg war party retaliated by killing Mathew's son and two servants on his plantation. {{Citation needed|reason=Whole paragraph unsubstantiated|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn retaliation, a Virginian militia led by Nathaniel Bacon entered Maryland, attacked the Doeg and besieged the Susquehannock. This precipitated the general reaction against natives by the Virginia Colony that resulted in \"Bacon's Rebellion\". In 1676 Bacon took his armed force to the Green Dragon Swamp on the upper Pamunkey River where he killed nearly fifty Pamunkey Indians, which lead to the chief Cockacoeske issuing orders to the rest of the tribe to escape. She ordered her tribe to not harm anyone and stay true to their treaty of peace.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ethan A. Schmidt|date=2012|title=Cockacoeske, Weroansqua of the Pamunkeys, and Indian Resistance in Seventeenth-Century Virginia|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5250/amerindiquar.36.3.0288|journal=American Indian Quarterly|volume=36|issue=3|pages=288|doi=10.5250/amerindiquar.36.3.0288|issn=0095-182X}}</ref> Thousands of Virginians from all [[Social class in the United States|classes]] (including those in indentured servitude) and [[Race and ethnicity in the United States|races]] rose up in arms against Berkeley, attacking Native Americans, chasing Berkeley from [[Jamestown, Virginia]], and ultimately torching the capital. The rebellion was first suppressed by a few armed merchant ships from London whose captains sided with Berkeley and the loyalists.<ref name=\"Webb1995\">{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&pg=PA87|accessdate=February 1, 2013|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|pages=87\u201393}}</ref> Government forces from England arrived soon after and spent several years defeating pockets of resistance and reforming the colonial government to be once more under direct royal control.<ref>{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&pg=PA10|accessdate=February 1, 2013|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first rebellion in the [[Thirteen Colonies|American colonies]] in which discontented frontiersmen took part (a somewhat similar uprising in [[History of Maryland|Maryland]] involving [[John Coode (Governor of Maryland)|John Coode]] and [[Josias Fendall]] took place shortly afterwards). The alliance between [[Indentured servitude in the Americas|European indentured servants]] and [[List of ethnic groups of Africa|Africans]] (many [[Slavery in the United States|enslaved]] until death or freed), united by their bond-servitude, disturbed the ruling class. The ruling class responded by hardening the racial caste of slavery in an attempt to divide the two races from subsequent united uprisings with the passage of the [[Virginia Slave Codes of 1705]].<ref name=Foner>Eric Foner, ''Give Me Liberty!: An American History'' (New York: W.W. Norton & Company, 2009), p. 100.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/aia/part1/1p274.html \"Bacon's Rebellion\"], ''Africans in America, Part 1'', PBS, accessed March 25, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web |accessdate=March 25, 2008 |title= Green Spring Plantation |work= Historic Jamestowne, National Park Service.\n|url= http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/green-spring-plantation.htm}}</ref> While the farmers did not succeed in their initial goal of driving the Native Americans from Virginia, the rebellion resulted in Berkeley being recalled to England.\n\n== Motives ==\nThe immediate cause of the rebellion was Governor Berkeley's refusal to retaliate for a series of Native American attacks on frontier settlements.  In addition, many colonists wished to attack and claim  Native American frontier land westward, but they were denied permission by Gov. Berkeley.<ref name=\"Foner\" />  Many of these colonists were former indentured servants whose contracts had terminated and who were now free, looking for land.\n\nModern historians have suggested the rebellion may have been a power play by Bacon against Berkeley and his favoritism towards certain members of the court. While Bacon was on the court, he was not within Berkeley's inner circle of council members and disagreed with him on many issues.  Bacon's financial backers included men of wealth from outside Berkeley's circle of influence.<ref name=Foner />\n\nHistorian Peter Thompson argues that Bacon's motivation was a personal vendetta between  Berkeley and him. However, Bacon's followers used the rebellion as an effort to gain government recognition of the shared interests among all social classes of the colony in protecting the \"commonality\" and advancing its welfare.<ref>Peter Thompson, \"The Thief, the Householder, and the Commons: Languages of Class in Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''William and Mary Quarterly'' (2006) 63#2 pp 253-280 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3877353 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n== Rebellion ==\nWhen Sir William Berkeley refused to retaliate against the Native Americans, farmers gathered around at the report of a new raiding party. Nathaniel Bacon arrived with a quantity of brandy; after it was distributed, he was elected leader. Against Berkeley's orders, the group struck south until they came to the [[Occaneechi]] people. After convincing the Occaneechi to attack the [[Susquehannock]], Bacon and his men followed by killing most of the men, women, and children at the village. Upon their return, they discovered that Berkeley had called for new elections to the Burgesses to better address the Native American raids.<ref>John Berry, Francis Moryson, and Herbert Jefferys, \"A True Narrative of the Rise, Progress and Cessation of the Late Rebellion in Virginia, Most Humbly an Impartially Recorded by His Majesties Commissioners, Appointed to inquire into the Affairs of the Said Colony\", Ed. by Charles Andrews, in ''Narrative of the Insurrections 1675 to 1690'', New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1915, pp. 111\u2013113.</ref>\n\n[[File:A Fair Mark - Shoot.jpg|thumb|Governor Berkeley baring his breast for Bacon to shoot after refusing him a commission (1895 engraving)]]\nThe recomposed [[House of Burgesses]] enacted a number of sweeping reforms (known as [[Bacon's Laws]]). (Bacon was not serving his duty in the House; rather, he was at his plantation miles away.) It limited the powers of the governor and restored suffrage rights to landless freemen.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Susan P. Castillo|author2=Ivy Schweitzer|title=The literatures of colonial America|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|year=2001|pages=[https://archive.org/details/literaturesofcol0000unse/page/225 225]|isbn=978-0-631-21125-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/literaturesofcol0000unse/page/225}}</ref>\n\nAfter passage of these laws, Nathaniel Bacon arrived with 500 followers in Jamestown to demand a commission to lead militia against the Native Americans. The governor, however, refused to yield to the pressure. When Bacon had his men take aim at Berkeley, he responded by \"baring his breast\" to Bacon and told Bacon to shoot him. Seeing that the governor would not be moved, Bacon then had his men take aim at the assembled burgesses, who quickly granted Bacon his commission. Bacon had earlier been promised a commission before he retired to his estate if he maintained \"good\" behavior for two weeks. While Bacon was at Jamestown with his small army, eight colonists were killed on the frontier in Henrico County (from where he marched) owing to a lack of manpower on the frontier.<ref>John Berry, Francis Moryson, and Herbert Jefferys, \"A True Narrative of the Rise, Progress and Cessation of the Late Rebellion in Virginia, Most Humbly an Impartially Recorded by His Majesties Commissioners, Appointed to inquire into the Affairs of the Said Colony.\" Ed. by Charles Andrews, in ''Narrative of the Insurrections 1675 to 1690'', (Charles Scribner's Sons: New York, 1915), 116.</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 1676, Bacon and his army issued the \"[[Declaration of the People]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/bacons-rebellion.htm|title=Bacon's Rebellion|work=nps.gov|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=October 6, 2015|last=McCulley|first=Susan|date=June 1987}}</ref> The declaration criticized Berkeley's administration in detail. It leveled several accusations against Berkeley:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.let.rug.nl/usa/documents/1651-1700/bacons-declaration-in-the-name-of-the-people-30-july-1676.php|title=Bacon's Declaration in the Name of the People 30 July 1676|last=|first=|date=|publisher=University of Groningen|access-date=November 12, 2016 }}</ref>\n# that \"upon specious pretense of public works [he] raised great unjust taxes upon the commonality\";\n# advancing favorites to high public offices;\n# monopolizing the beaver trade with the Native Americans;\n# being pro-Native American.\n\n[[File:The Burning of Jamestown.jpg|thumb|left|A 19th-century engraving depicting the burning of Jamestown]]\n\nAfter months of conflict, Bacon's forces, numbering 300-500 men, moved to [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]]. They burned the colonial capital to the ground on September 19, 1676. Outnumbered, Berkeley retreated across the river.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Edward Channing |author2=Eva G. Moore|title=A history of the United States|publisher=Macmillan|year=1908|pages=88}}</ref>\n\nBefore an English naval squadron led by [[Thomas Larimore]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Webb|first1=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|date=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse NY|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=August 1, 2017|language=en}}</ref> could arrive to aid Berkeley and his forces, Bacon died from [[dysentery]] on October 26, 1676.<ref>Bragdon Kathleen J., ''The Columbia Guide to American Indians of the Northeast'', Columbia University Press, 2005, p. 112.</ref><ref>''Narratives of the Insurrections, 1675\u20131690'', ed. Charles McLean Andrews, New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1915, p. 139.</ref> [[John Ingram (member of Bacon's Rebellion)|John Ingram]] took over leadership of the rebellion, but many followers drifted away. The rebellion did not last long after that. Berkeley launched a series of successful amphibious attacks across the Chesapeake Bay and defeated the rebels. His forces defeated the small pockets of insurgents spread across the [[Tidewater (geographic term)|Tidewater]]. Thomas Grantham, a captain of a ship cruising the York River, used cunning and force to disarm the rebels. He tricked his way into the garrison of the rebellion, and promised to pardon everyone involved once they got back onto the ship. However, once they were safely in the hold, he trained the ship's guns on them and disarmed the rebellion. Through various other tactics, the other rebel garrisons were likewise overcome.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zinn|first=Howard|title=A People's History Of The United States|year=1997|publisher=The New York Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-56584-724-5|pages=281}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Illustration of Ruins of Jamestown 1676.jpg|thumb|Ruins of Jamestown (1878 engraving)]]\nThe 71-year-old governor Berkeley returned to the burned capital and a looted home at the end of January 1677.<ref>{{cite web\n|accessdate=March 25, 2008 |title= Green Spring Plantation |work= Historic Jamestowne |url= http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/green-spring-plantation.htm}}</ref> His wife described Green Spring in a letter to her cousin:\n\n<blockquote>It looked like one of those the boys pull down at [[Shrovetide]], and was almost as much to repair as if it had been new to build, and no sign that ever there had been a fence around it...<ref>Waldrup, Carole Chandler, ''Colonial Women: 23 Europeans Who Helped Build a Nation'', McFarland, 1999, p. 86.</ref></blockquote>\n\nBacon's wealthy landowning followers returned their loyalty to the Virginia government after Bacon's death. Governor Berkeley returned to power.  He seized the property of several rebels for the colony and executed 23 men by hanging,<ref name=\"Geiter\">Geiter, Mary K., William Arthur Speck, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Uo8dBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA63 Colonial America: From Jamestown to Yorktown]'', Macmillan, 2002, p. 63</ref> including the former governor of the [[Albemarle Sound]] colony, [[William Drummond (colonial governor)|William Drummond]], and the collector of customs, Giles Bland.<ref>Tyler, Lyon G., ''Encyclopedia of Virginia Biography'', Lewis historical publishing company, 1915, Vol. I p. 226</ref>\n\nAfter an investigative committee returned its report to King [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], Berkeley was relieved of the governorship, and recalled to England.  \"The fear of civil war among whites frightened Virginia's ruling elite, who took steps to consolidate power and improve their image: for example, restoration of property qualifications for voting, reducing taxes, and adoption of a more aggressive American Indian policy.\"<ref name=Foner /> Charles II was reported to have commented, \"That old fool has put to death more people in that naked country than I did here for the murder of my father.\"<ref>Fiske, John, ''Old Virginia and Her Neighbours'', Houghton, Mifflin and Co., 1902, p. 110</ref>  No record of the king's comments have been found; the origin of the story appears to have been colonial myth that arose at least 30 years after the events; the king prided himself on the clemency he had shown to his father's enemies.<ref>Washburn, ''The Governor and the Rebel'', p. 139</ref> Berkeley left his wife \"Frances Berkeley\" in Virginia and returned to England; She sent him a letter to let him know that the current governor was making a bet that the king would refuse to receive him. However William Berkeley died as soon as he landed in England.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WESTBURY|first=SUSAN|date=March 2004|title=Theatre and Power in Bacon's Rebellion: Virginia, 1676\u201377|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0268117x.2004.10555536|journal=The Seventeenth Century|volume=19|issue=1|pages=69\u201386|doi=10.1080/0268117x.2004.10555536|issn=0268-117X}}</ref>\n\n[[Indentured servants]] both black and white joined the frontier rebellion.  Seeing them united in a cause alarmed the ruling class.  Historians believe the rebellion hastened the hardening of racial lines associated with slavery, as a way for planters and the colony to control some of the poor.<ref>[[William J. Cooper, Jr.|Cooper, William J.]], ''Liberty and Slavery: Southern Politics to 1860'', Univ of South Carolina Press, 2001, p. 9.</ref>\n\n== Historiography ==\n\nHistorians question whether the rebellion by Bacon against Berkeley in 1676 had any lasting significance for the more-successful [[American Revolution|revolution]] a century later.  The most idolizing portrait of Bacon is found in ''Torchbearer of the Revolution'' (1940) by [[Thomas Jefferson Wertenbaker]], which one scholar in 2011 called \"one of the worst books on Virginia that a reputable scholarly historian ever published.\"<ref>Tarter, Brent. \"Bacon's Rebellion, the Grievances of the People, and the Political Culture of Seventeenth-Century Virginia.\" The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography 119, no. 1 (2011): 6; Rice, James D. Tales from a Revolution:  Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America. Oxford University Press (Oxford:  2012.) Print. Pg. 204.</ref>  The central area of debate is Bacon's controversial character and complex disposition, as illustrated by [[Wilcomb Washburn]]'s ''The Governor and the Rebel'' (1957). Rather than singing Bacon's praises and chastising Berkeley's tyranny, Washburn found the roots of the rebellion in the colonists' intolerable demand to \"authorize the slaughter and dispossession of the innocent as well as the guilty.\"<ref>Washburn, ''The Governor and the Rebel'', p. 163</ref>\n\nMore nuanced approaches on Berkeley's supposed tyranny or mismanagement entertained specialist historians throughout the middle of the century, leading to a diversification of factors responsible for Virginia's contemporary instability. [[Wesley Frank Craven]] in the 1968 publication ''The Colonies in Transition'' argues that Berkeley's greatest failings took place during the revolt, near the end of his life.<ref>Craven, Wesley Frank.  The Colonies in Transition: 1669\u20131713.  Harper & Row, Publishers (New York:  1968.) Print.</ref>  [[Bernard Bailyn]] pushed the novel thesis that it was a question of access to resources, a failure to fully transplant Old World society to New.<ref>Bailyn, Bernard, \"Politics and Social Structure in Virginia.\" Seventeenth-Century America, pp. 90-108.</ref>\n\n[[Edmund S. Morgan]]'s classic 1975 ''[[American Slavery, American Freedom]]:  The Ordeal of Colonial Virginia'' connected the calamity of Bacon's Rebellion, namely the potential for lower-class revolt, with the colony's transition over to slavery: \"..But for those with eyes to see, there was an obvious lesson in the rebellion.  Resentment of an alien race might be more powerful than resentment of an upper class. Virginians did not immediately grasp it.  It would sink in as time went on ...\"<ref>Morgan, Edmund S.  ''American Slavery, American Freedom:  The Ordeal of Colonial Virginia''.  W.W. Norton & Company, Inc. (New York:  1975.) 270.</ref>\n\nJames Rice's 2012 narrative ''Tales from a Revolution: Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America'', whose emphasis on Bacon's flaws echoes ''The Governor and the Rebel'', integrates the rebellion into a larger story emphasizing the actions of multiple Native Americans, as well as placing it in the context of English politics; in this telling, the climax of Bacon's Rebellion comes with the Glorious Revolution of 1688/89.<ref>Rice, James D. ''Tales from a Revolution:  Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America''. Oxford University Press (Oxford:  2012.) Print.</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n<!-- This text duplicates a section at the Nathaniel Bacon article, so the two should likely be edited in tandem -->\nDespite recent historians' views of the conflict, many in the early [[United States]], including [[Thomas Jefferson]], saw Bacon as a patriot and believed that Bacon's Rebellion was a prelude to the later [[American Revolution]] against English colonial rule.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.org/foundation/journal/Spring15/bacon.cfm|title=Nathaniel Bacon, Saint or Sinner?|last=Gardner|first=Andrew G.|date=Spring 2015|website=Colonial Williamsburg Foundation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.virginiahistory.org/node/2292|title=Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia in the years 1675 & 1676 {{!}} Virginia Museum of History & Culture|website=www.virginiahistory.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref> This understanding of the conflict was reflected in 20th-century commemorations, including a memorial window in [[Colonial Williamsburg]], and a prominent tablet in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] chamber of the [[Virginia State Capitol]] in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], which recalls Bacon as \"A great Patriot Leader of the Virginia People who died while defending their rights October 26, 1676.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://capclass.virginiageneralassembly.gov/High/AbouttheCapitol/CapitolHigh.html|title=About the Capitol \u2013 High School|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia General Assembly \u2013 Capitol Classroom|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref>\n\n== Use of scopolamine ==\n[[Robert Beverley, Jr.|Robert Beverley]] reported, in his 1705 book on the history of Virginia, that some British soldiers who had been dispatched to Jamestown to quell Bacon's Rebellion gathered and ate leaves of ''[[Datura stramonium]]'', and spent 11 days acting in bizarre and foolish ways before recovering.<ref>{{cite book|author=Karen Ordahl Kupperman|title=The Atlantic in World History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WnaDEZwMAyMC&pg=PA89|year=2012|publisher=Oxford UP|pages=89\u201390|isbn=978-0-19-533809-6}}</ref> This led to the plant being known as Jamestown weed, and later jimsonweed.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cockacoeske]], Pamunkey chief\n* [[Queen Ann (Pamunkey chief)]]\n* [[Bacon's Castle]]\n<!-- * [[Jamestown weed]]\u2014 a name for ''Datura stramonium'' that has its origins in a [[psychedelic drug|psychedelic]] incident that occurred during Bacon's Rebellion\n -->* [[Culpeper's Rebellion]]\nlove that chicken from popeyes\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Allen, Theodore W. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=OxwCQkCq4f0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Invention of the White Race, Vol. 2: The Origins of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America.]'' London: Verso (1997).\n* Billings, Warren M. \"The Causes of Bacon's Rebellion: Some Suggestions,\" ''Virginia Magazine of History and Biography,'' 1970, Vol. 78 Issue 4, pp.&nbsp;409\u2013435\n* Cave, Alfred A. \"Lethal Encounters: Englishmen and Indians in Colonial Virginia\" (University of Nebraska Press, 2011) {{ISBN|978-0-8032-4834-2}} pp.&nbsp;147\u2013165\n* Cullen, Joseph P. \"Bacon's Rebellion,\" ''American History Illustrated,'' Dec 1968, Vol. 3 Issue 8, p.&nbsp;4 ff.\n* Rice, James D. \"Bacon's Rebellion in Indian Country,\" ''Journal of American History,'' vol. 101, no. 3 (Dec. 2014), pp.&nbsp;726\u2013750.\n* Tarter, Brent. \"Bacon's Rebellion, the Grievances of the People, and the Political Culture of Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''Virginia Magazine of History & Biography'' (2011) 119#1 pp 1\u201341.\n* Thompson, Peter. \"The Thief, the Householder, and the Commons: Languages of Class in Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''William & Mary Quarterly'' (2006) 63#2 pp 253\u2013280 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3877353 in JSTOR]\n* {{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676, the end of American independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0}}\n* Wertenbaker, Thomas Jefferson. ''Torchbearer of the Revolution: The Story of Bacon's Rebellion and its Leader'' (Princeton University Press, 1940)\n* Washburn, Wilcomb E. ''The Governor and the Rebel: A History of Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia'' (University of North Carolina Press for the Institute of Early American History and Culture, 1957)\n\n<!-- ===Primary sources=== -->* Wiseman, Samuel. ''Book of Record: The Official Account of Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia, 1676\u20131677'' (2006)\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Library resources about|onlinebooks=yes}}\n*[http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/bacon_s_rebellion_1676-1677 Bacon's Rebellion] at ''[[Encyclopedia Virginia]]''\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1676]]\n[[Category:1676 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Colonial Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Colonial American and Indian wars]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Virginia]]\n[[Category:17th-century rebellions]]\n[[Category:1676 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Jamestown, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Slave rebellions in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|1676 Virginia rebellion against the colonial government}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| latitude = \n| longitude = \n|image = Howard Pyle - The Burning of Jamestown.jpg\n|image_upright = 1.2\n|caption = ''The Burning of Jamestown'' by [[Howard Pyle]], c. 1905\n|date = 1676\n|place = [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]], [[Colony of Virginia]]\n| coordinates = <!-- type:landmark_region:US-VA -->\n| goals   = Change in Virginia's Indian-Frontier policy\n| methods = [[Demonstration (people)|Demonstrations]], [[vigilantes]]\n| status  = \n| result  = \n| concessions =\n| side1= [[Indentured servants|Common indentured servants]] and [[African-Americans|Enslaved Africans]]\n| side2= [[William Berkeley (governor)|Sir William Berkeley]], [[Colonial Governor of Virginia|Royal Colonial Governor]] appointed by the crown.\n| leadfigures1= [[Nathaniel Bacon (Virginia)|Nathaniel Bacon]] and\n [[John Ingram (Member of Bacon's Rebellion)|John Ingram]] \n| leadfigures2= [[William Berkeley (governor)|William Berkeley]]\n| casualties2= None\n| casualties1= '''Deaths''': 23 hanged<ref name=\"Geiter\" />\n| howmany2= 200\n| howmany1= 300\u2013500\n}}\n'''Bacon's Rebellion''' was an armed rebellion that took place 1676-1677 by [[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]] settlers led by [[Nathaniel Bacon (Virginia)|Nathaniel Bacon]] against the rule of Governor [[William Berkeley (governor)|William Berkeley]]. His grievances against the governor stemmed from Berkeley's dismissive policy to the political challenges of its western frontier, particularly leaving Bacon out of his inner circle and refusing to allow Bacon to take part in fur trading with [[Native American tribes in Virginia|Native Americans]], and Berkeley refusing Bacon a military commission that would allow him to fight and attack Native Americans at his own discretion. Attacks by the [[Doeg people]] are credited with inciting the popular uprising against Berkeley for failing to address the demands of the colonists regarding the safety of the frontier. The Doeg people had both traded and made war on the Virginia frontier.\n\nStarting in the 1650s, as English colonists began to settle the Northern Neck frontier, then known as Chicacoan (Secocowon), some Doeg, Patawomeck and Rappahannock began moving into the region as well and joined local tribes in disputing the settlers' claims to land and resources. In July 1666, the colonists declared war on them. By 1669, colonists had patented the land on the west of the Potomac as far north as My Lord's Island. By 1670, they had driven most of the Doeg out of the Virginia colony and into Maryland\u2014apart from those living beside the Nanzatico/Portobago in Caroline County, Virginia.\n\nThe English continued to harass the Doeg on the Northern Neck and in July 1675, a Doeg raiding party crossed the Potomac and stole hogs from Thomas Mathew, in retaliation for him not paying them for traded goods. Mathew and other colonists pursued them to Maryland and killed a group of Doeg, as well as innocent Susquehannock. A Doeg war party retaliated by killing Mathew's son and two servants on his plantation. {{Citation needed|reason=Whole paragraph unsubstantiated|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn retaliation, a Virginian militia led by Nathaniel Bacon entered Maryland, attacked the Doeg and besieged the Susquehannock. This precipitated the general reaction against natives by the Virginia Colony that resulted in \"Bacon's Rebellion\". In 1676 Bacon took his armed force to the Green Dragon Swamp on the upper Pamunkey River where he killed nearly fifty Pamunkey Indians, which lead to the chief Cockacoeske issuing orders to the rest of the tribe to escape. She ordered her tribe to not harm anyone and stay true to their treaty of peace.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ethan A. Schmidt|date=2012|title=Cockacoeske, Weroansqua of the Pamunkeys, and Indian Resistance in Seventeenth-Century Virginia|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5250/amerindiquar.36.3.0288|journal=American Indian Quarterly|volume=36|issue=3|pages=288|doi=10.5250/amerindiquar.36.3.0288|issn=0095-182X}}</ref> Thousands of Virginians from all [[Social class in the United States|classes]] (including those in indentured servitude) and [[Race and ethnicity in the United States|races]] rose up in arms against Berkeley, attacking Native Americans, chasing Berkeley from [[Jamestown, Virginia]], and ultimately torching the capital. The rebellion was first suppressed by a few armed merchant ships from London whose captains sided with Berkeley and the loyalists.<ref name=\"Webb1995\">{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&pg=PA87|accessdate=February 1, 2013|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|pages=87\u201393}}</ref> Government forces from England arrived soon after and spent several years defeating pockets of resistance and reforming the colonial government to be once more under direct royal control.<ref>{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&pg=PA10|accessdate=February 1, 2013|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|pages=10\u201313}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first rebellion in the [[Thirteen Colonies|American colonies]] in which discontented frontiersmen took part (a somewhat similar uprising in [[History of Maryland|Maryland]] involving [[John Coode (Governor of Maryland)|John Coode]] and [[Josias Fendall]] took place shortly afterwards). The alliance between [[Indentured servitude in the Americas|European indentured servants]] and [[List of ethnic groups of Africa|Africans]] (many [[Slavery in the United States|enslaved]] until death or freed), united by their bond-servitude, disturbed the ruling class. The ruling class responded by hardening the racial caste of slavery in an attempt to divide the two races from subsequent united uprisings with the passage of the [[Virginia Slave Codes of 1705]].<ref name=Foner>Eric Foner, ''Give Me Liberty!: An American History'' (New York: W.W. Norton & Company, 2009), p. 100.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/aia/part1/1p274.html \"Bacon's Rebellion\"], ''Africans in America, Part 1'', PBS, accessed March 25, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web |accessdate=March 25, 2008 |title= Green Spring Plantation |work= Historic Jamestowne, National Park Service.\n|url= http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/green-spring-plantation.htm}}</ref> While the farmers did not succeed in their initial goal of driving the Native Americans from Virginia, the rebellion resulted in Berkeley being recalled to England.\n\n== Motives ==\nThe immediate cause of the rebellion was Governor Berkeley's refusal to retaliate for a series of Native American attacks on frontier settlements.  In addition, many colonists wished to attack and claim  Native American frontier land westward, but they were denied permission by Gov. Berkeley.<ref name=\"Foner\" />  Many of these colonists were former indentured servants whose contracts had terminated and who were now free, looking for land.\n\nModern historians have suggested the rebellion may have been a power play by Bacon against Berkeley and his favoritism towards certain members of the court. While Bacon was on the court, he was not within Berkeley's inner circle of council members and disagreed with him on many issues.  Bacon's financial backers included men of wealth from outside Berkeley's circle of influence.<ref name=Foner />\n\nHistorian Peter Thompson argues that Bacon's motivation was a personal vendetta between  Berkeley and him. However, Bacon's followers used the rebellion as an effort to gain government recognition of the shared interests among all social classes of the colony in protecting the \"commonality\" and advancing its welfare.<ref>Peter Thompson, \"The Thief, the Householder, and the Commons: Languages of Class in Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''William and Mary Quarterly'' (2006) 63#2 pp 253-280 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3877353 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n== Rebellion ==\nWhen Sir William Berkeley refused to retaliate against the Native Americans, farmers gathered around at the report of a new raiding party. Nathaniel Bacon arrived with a quantity of brandy; after it was distributed, he was elected leader. Against Berkeley's orders, the group struck south until they came to the [[Occaneechi]] people. After convincing the Occaneechi to attack the [[Susquehannock]], Bacon and his men followed by killing most of the men, women, and children at the village. Upon their return, they discovered that Berkeley had called for new elections to the Burgesses to better address the Native American raids.<ref>John Berry, Francis Moryson, and Herbert Jefferys, \"A True Narrative of the Rise, Progress and Cessation of the Late Rebellion in Virginia, Most Humbly an Impartially Recorded by His Majesties Commissioners, Appointed to inquire into the Affairs of the Said Colony\", Ed. by Charles Andrews, in ''Narrative of the Insurrections 1675 to 1690'', New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1915, pp. 111\u2013113.</ref>\n\n[[File:A Fair Mark - Shoot.jpg|thumb|Governor Berkeley baring his breast for Bacon to shoot after refusing him a commission (1895 engraving)]]\nThe recomposed [[House of Burgesses]] enacted a number of sweeping reforms (known as [[Bacon's Laws]]). (Bacon was not serving his duty in the House; rather, he was at his plantation miles away.) It limited the powers of the governor and restored suffrage rights to landless freemen.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Susan P. Castillo|author2=Ivy Schweitzer|title=The literatures of colonial America|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|year=2001|pages=[https://archive.org/details/literaturesofcol0000unse/page/225 225]|isbn=978-0-631-21125-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/literaturesofcol0000unse/page/225}}</ref>\n\nAfter passage of these laws, Nathaniel Bacon arrived with 500 followers in Jamestown to demand a commission to lead militia against the Native Americans. The governor, however, refused to yield to the pressure. When Bacon had his men take aim at Berkeley, he responded by \"baring his breast\" to Bacon and told Bacon to shoot him. Seeing that the governor would not be moved, Bacon then had his men take aim at the assembled burgesses, who quickly granted Bacon his commission. Bacon had earlier been promised a commission before he retired to his estate if he maintained \"good\" behavior for two weeks. While Bacon was at Jamestown with his small army, eight colonists were killed on the frontier in Henrico County (from where he marched) owing to a lack of manpower on the frontier.<ref>John Berry, Francis Moryson, and Herbert Jefferys, \"A True Narrative of the Rise, Progress and Cessation of the Late Rebellion in Virginia, Most Humbly an Impartially Recorded by His Majesties Commissioners, Appointed to inquire into the Affairs of the Said Colony.\" Ed. by Charles Andrews, in ''Narrative of the Insurrections 1675 to 1690'', (Charles Scribner's Sons: New York, 1915), 116.</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 1676, Bacon and his army issued the \"[[Declaration of the People]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/bacons-rebellion.htm|title=Bacon's Rebellion|work=nps.gov|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=October 6, 2015|last=McCulley|first=Susan|date=June 1987}}</ref> The declaration criticized Berkeley's administration in detail. It leveled several accusations against Berkeley:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.let.rug.nl/usa/documents/1651-1700/bacons-declaration-in-the-name-of-the-people-30-july-1676.php|title=Bacon's Declaration in the Name of the People 30 July 1676|last=|first=|date=|publisher=University of Groningen|access-date=November 12, 2016 }}</ref>\n# that \"upon specious pretense of public works [he] raised great unjust taxes upon the commonality\";\n# advancing favorites to high public offices;\n# monopolizing the beaver trade with the Native Americans;\n# being pro-Native American.\n\n[[File:The Burning of Jamestown.jpg|thumb|left|A 19th-century engraving depicting the burning of Jamestown]]\n\nAfter months of conflict, Bacon's forces, numbering 300-500 men, moved to [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]]. They burned the colonial capital to the ground on September 19, 1676. Outnumbered, Berkeley retreated across the river.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Edward Channing |author2=Eva G. Moore|title=A history of the United States|publisher=Macmillan|year=1908|pages=88}}</ref>\n\nBefore an English naval squadron led by [[Thomas Larimore]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Webb|first1=Stephen Saunders|title=1676: The End of American Independence|date=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse NY|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=August 1, 2017|language=en}}</ref> could arrive to aid Berkeley and his forces, Bacon died from [[dysentery]] on October 26, 1676.<ref>Bragdon Kathleen J., ''The Columbia Guide to American Indians of the Northeast'', Columbia University Press, 2005, p. 112.</ref><ref>''Narratives of the Insurrections, 1675\u20131690'', ed. Charles McLean Andrews, New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1915, p. 139.</ref> [[John Ingram (member of Bacon's Rebellion)|John Ingram]] took over leadership of the rebellion, but many followers drifted away. The rebellion did not last long after that. Berkeley launched a series of successful amphibious attacks across the Chesapeake Bay and defeated the rebels. His forces defeated the small pockets of insurgents spread across the [[Tidewater (geographic term)|Tidewater]]. Thomas Grantham, a captain of a ship cruising the York River, used cunning and force to disarm the rebels. He tricked his way into the garrison of the rebellion, and promised to pardon everyone involved once they got back onto the ship. However, once they were safely in the hold, he trained the ship's guns on them and disarmed the rebellion. Through various other tactics, the other rebel garrisons were likewise overcome.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zinn|first=Howard|title=A People's History Of The United States|year=1997|publisher=The New York Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-56584-724-5|pages=281}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Illustration of Ruins of Jamestown 1676.jpg|thumb|Ruins of Jamestown (1878 engraving)]]\nThe 71-year-old governor Berkeley returned to the burned capital and a looted home at the end of January 1677.<ref>{{cite web\n|accessdate=March 25, 2008 |title= Green Spring Plantation |work= Historic Jamestowne |url= http://www.nps.gov/jame/historyculture/green-spring-plantation.htm}}</ref> His wife described Green Spring in a letter to her cousin:\n\n<blockquote>It looked like one of those the boys pull down at [[Shrovetide]], and was almost as much to repair as if it had been new to build, and no sign that ever there had been a fence around it...<ref>Waldrup, Carole Chandler, ''Colonial Women: 23 Europeans Who Helped Build a Nation'', McFarland, 1999, p. 86.</ref></blockquote>\n\nBacon's wealthy landowning followers returned their loyalty to the Virginia government after Bacon's death. Governor Berkeley returned to power.  He seized the property of several rebels for the colony and executed 23 men by hanging,<ref name=\"Geiter\">Geiter, Mary K., William Arthur Speck, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Uo8dBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA63 Colonial America: From Jamestown to Yorktown]'', Macmillan, 2002, p. 63</ref> including the former governor of the [[Albemarle Sound]] colony, [[William Drummond (colonial governor)|William Drummond]], and the collector of customs, Giles Bland.<ref>Tyler, Lyon G., ''Encyclopedia of Virginia Biography'', Lewis historical publishing company, 1915, Vol. I p. 226</ref>\n\nAfter an investigative committee returned its report to King [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], Berkeley was relieved of the governorship, and recalled to England.  \"The fear of civil war among whites frightened Virginia's ruling elite, who took steps to consolidate power and improve their image: for example, restoration of property qualifications for voting, reducing taxes, and adoption of a more aggressive American Indian policy.\"<ref name=Foner /> Charles II was reported to have commented, \"That old fool has put to death more people in that naked country than I did here for the murder of my father.\"<ref>Fiske, John, ''Old Virginia and Her Neighbours'', Houghton, Mifflin and Co., 1902, p. 110</ref>  No record of the king's comments have been found; the origin of the story appears to have been colonial myth that arose at least 30 years after the events; the king prided himself on the clemency he had shown to his father's enemies.<ref>Washburn, ''The Governor and the Rebel'', p. 139</ref> Berkeley left his wife \"Frances Berkeley\" in Virginia and returned to England; She sent him a letter to let him know that the current governor was making a bet that the king would refuse to receive him. However William Berkeley died as soon as he landed in England.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WESTBURY|first=SUSAN|date=March 2004|title=Theatre and Power in Bacon's Rebellion: Virginia, 1676\u201377|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0268117x.2004.10555536|journal=The Seventeenth Century|volume=19|issue=1|pages=69\u201386|doi=10.1080/0268117x.2004.10555536|issn=0268-117X}}</ref>\n\n[[Indentured servants]] both black and white joined the frontier rebellion.  Seeing them united in a cause alarmed the ruling class.  Historians believe the rebellion hastened the hardening of racial lines associated with slavery, as a way for planters and the colony to control some of the poor.<ref>[[William J. Cooper, Jr.|Cooper, William J.]], ''Liberty and Slavery: Southern Politics to 1860'', Univ of South Carolina Press, 2001, p. 9.</ref>\n\n== Historiography ==\n\nHistorians question whether the rebellion by Bacon against Berkeley in 1676 had any lasting significance for the more-successful [[American Revolution|revolution]] a century later.  The most idolizing portrait of Bacon is found in ''Torchbearer of the Revolution'' (1940) by [[Thomas Jefferson Wertenbaker]], which one scholar in 2011 called \"one of the worst books on Virginia that a reputable scholarly historian ever published.\"<ref>Tarter, Brent. \"Bacon's Rebellion, the Grievances of the People, and the Political Culture of Seventeenth-Century Virginia.\" The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography 119, no. 1 (2011): 6; Rice, James D. Tales from a Revolution:  Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America. Oxford University Press (Oxford:  2012.) Print. Pg. 204.</ref>  The central area of debate is Bacon's controversial character and complex disposition, as illustrated by [[Wilcomb Washburn]]'s ''The Governor and the Rebel'' (1957). Rather than singing Bacon's praises and chastising Berkeley's tyranny, Washburn found the roots of the rebellion in the colonists' intolerable demand to \"authorize the slaughter and dispossession of the innocent as well as the guilty.\"<ref>Washburn, ''The Governor and the Rebel'', p. 163</ref>\n\nMore nuanced approaches on Berkeley's supposed tyranny or mismanagement entertained specialist historians throughout the middle of the century, leading to a diversification of factors responsible for Virginia's contemporary instability. [[Wesley Frank Craven]] in the 1968 publication ''The Colonies in Transition'' argues that Berkeley's greatest failings took place during the revolt, near the end of his life.<ref>Craven, Wesley Frank.  The Colonies in Transition: 1669\u20131713.  Harper & Row, Publishers (New York:  1968.) Print.</ref>  [[Bernard Bailyn]] pushed the novel thesis that it was a question of access to resources, a failure to fully transplant Old World society to New.<ref>Bailyn, Bernard, \"Politics and Social Structure in Virginia.\" Seventeenth-Century America, pp. 90-108.</ref>\n\n[[Edmund S. Morgan]]'s classic 1975 ''[[American Slavery, American Freedom]]:  The Ordeal of Colonial Virginia'' connected the calamity of Bacon's Rebellion, namely the potential for lower-class revolt, with the colony's transition over to slavery: \"..But for those with eyes to see, there was an obvious lesson in the rebellion.  Resentment of an alien race might be more powerful than resentment of an upper class. Virginians did not immediately grasp it.  It would sink in as time went on ...\"<ref>Morgan, Edmund S.  ''American Slavery, American Freedom:  The Ordeal of Colonial Virginia''.  W.W. Norton & Company, Inc. (New York:  1975.) 270.</ref>\n\nJames Rice's 2012 narrative ''Tales from a Revolution: Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America'', whose emphasis on Bacon's flaws echoes ''The Governor and the Rebel'', integrates the rebellion into a larger story emphasizing the actions of multiple Native Americans, as well as placing it in the context of English politics; in this telling, the climax of Bacon's Rebellion comes with the Glorious Revolution of 1688/89.<ref>Rice, James D. ''Tales from a Revolution:  Bacon's Rebellion and the Transformation of Early America''. Oxford University Press (Oxford:  2012.) Print.</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n<!-- This text duplicates a section at the Nathaniel Bacon article, so the two should likely be edited in tandem -->\nDespite recent historians' views of the conflict, many in the early [[United States]], including [[Thomas Jefferson]], saw Bacon as a patriot and believed that Bacon's Rebellion was a prelude to the later [[American Revolution]] against English colonial rule.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.history.org/foundation/journal/Spring15/bacon.cfm|title=Nathaniel Bacon, Saint or Sinner?|last=Gardner|first=Andrew G.|date=Spring 2015|website=Colonial Williamsburg Foundation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.virginiahistory.org/node/2292|title=Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia in the years 1675 & 1676 {{!}} Virginia Museum of History & Culture|website=www.virginiahistory.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref> This understanding of the conflict was reflected in 20th-century commemorations, including a memorial window in [[Colonial Williamsburg]], and a prominent tablet in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] chamber of the [[Virginia State Capitol]] in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], which recalls Bacon as \"A great Patriot Leader of the Virginia People who died while defending their rights October 26, 1676.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://capclass.virginiageneralassembly.gov/High/AbouttheCapitol/CapitolHigh.html|title=About the Capitol \u2013 High School|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia General Assembly \u2013 Capitol Classroom|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref>\n\n== Use of scopolamine ==\n[[Robert Beverley, Jr.|Robert Beverley]] reported, in his 1705 book on the history of Virginia, that some British soldiers who had been dispatched to Jamestown to quell Bacon's Rebellion gathered and ate leaves of ''[[Datura stramonium]]'', and spent 11 days acting in bizarre and foolish ways before recovering.<ref>{{cite book|author=Karen Ordahl Kupperman|title=The Atlantic in World History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WnaDEZwMAyMC&pg=PA89|year=2012|publisher=Oxford UP|pages=89\u201390|isbn=978-0-19-533809-6}}</ref> This led to the plant being known as Jamestown weed, and later jimsonweed.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cockacoeske]], Pamunkey chief\n* [[Queen Ann (Pamunkey chief)]]\n* [[Bacon's Castle]]\n<!-- * [[Jamestown weed]]\u2014 a name for ''Datura stramonium'' that has its origins in a [[psychedelic drug|psychedelic]] incident that occurred during Bacon's Rebellion\n -->* [[Culpeper's Rebellion]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Allen, Theodore W. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=OxwCQkCq4f0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Invention of the White Race, Vol. 2: The Origins of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America.]'' London: Verso (1997).\n* Billings, Warren M. \"The Causes of Bacon's Rebellion: Some Suggestions,\" ''Virginia Magazine of History and Biography,'' 1970, Vol. 78 Issue 4, pp.&nbsp;409\u2013435\n* Cave, Alfred A. \"Lethal Encounters: Englishmen and Indians in Colonial Virginia\" (University of Nebraska Press, 2011) {{ISBN|978-0-8032-4834-2}} pp.&nbsp;147\u2013165\n* Cullen, Joseph P. \"Bacon's Rebellion,\" ''American History Illustrated,'' Dec 1968, Vol. 3 Issue 8, p.&nbsp;4 ff.\n* Rice, James D. \"Bacon's Rebellion in Indian Country,\" ''Journal of American History,'' vol. 101, no. 3 (Dec. 2014), pp.&nbsp;726\u2013750.\n* Tarter, Brent. \"Bacon's Rebellion, the Grievances of the People, and the Political Culture of Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''Virginia Magazine of History & Biography'' (2011) 119#1 pp 1\u201341.\n* Thompson, Peter. \"The Thief, the Householder, and the Commons: Languages of Class in Seventeenth-Century Virginia,\" ''William & Mary Quarterly'' (2006) 63#2 pp 253\u2013280 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3877353 in JSTOR]\n* {{cite book|last=Webb|first=Stephen Saunders|title=1676, the end of American independence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P1etgd8yjfkC|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0361-0}}\n* Wertenbaker, Thomas Jefferson. ''Torchbearer of the Revolution: The Story of Bacon's Rebellion and its Leader'' (Princeton University Press, 1940)\n* Washburn, Wilcomb E. ''The Governor and the Rebel: A History of Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia'' (University of North Carolina Press for the Institute of Early American History and Culture, 1957)\n\n<!-- ===Primary sources=== -->* Wiseman, Samuel. ''Book of Record: The Official Account of Bacon's Rebellion in Virginia, 1676\u20131677'' (2006)\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Library resources about|onlinebooks=yes}}\n*[http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/bacon_s_rebellion_1676-1677 Bacon's Rebellion] at ''[[Encyclopedia Virginia]]''\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1676]]\n[[Category:1676 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Colonial Virginia]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Colonial American and Indian wars]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Virginia]]\n[[Category:17th-century rebellions]]\n[[Category:1676 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Jamestown, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Slave rebellions in North America]]\n", "name_user": "98.222.107.198", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacon%27s_Rebellion"}
{"title_page": "Cameron Boyce", "text_new": "{{About|the actor|the cricketer|Cameron Boyce (cricketer)}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Cameron Boyce\n| image        = Cameron Boyce in october 2017.jpg\n| caption      = Boyce in 2017\n| birth_name   = Cameron Mica Boyce\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1999|5|28}}\n| birth_place  = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2019|7|6|1999|5|28}}\n| death_place  = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| death_cause  = <!-- EST\u00c1 TO BUENO instructions, only included when the cause of death has significance for the subject's notability -->\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2008\u20132019\n| television   = <!-- per inbox instructions, television programs presented by or closely associated with the subject -->\n}}\n\n'''Cameron Mica Boyce'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/07/obituaries/cameron-boyce-dead.html|title=Cameron Boyce, Disney Channel Star, Dies at 20|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 18, 2019}}</ref> (May 28, 1999 \u2013 July 6, 2019) was an American actor. After making his first acting appearance in a [[Panic! at the Disco]] music video, he made his film debut in ''[[Mirrors (film)|Mirrors]]'' in 2008. Boyce then went on to star as Luke Ross in [[Disney Channel]]'s [[comedy]] series ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' from 2011 to 2015. He also starred in feature films ''[[Eagle Eye]]'', ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'', and ''[[Grown Ups 2]]''. He was also known for his role as Carlos in the three ''[[Descendants (franchise)|Descendants]]'' television films and for his lead role as Conor in [[Disney XD]]'s comedy series ''[[Gamer's Guide to Pretty Much Everything]]''. Boyce also did voice acting for various works, such as Jake in ''[[Jake and the Never Land Pirates]]'' and Herman Schultz in ''[[Spider-Man (2017 TV series)|Spider-Man]]''. On July 6, 2019, Boyce died at the age of 20 due to [[sudden unexpected death in epilepsy|complications of epilepsy]].\n\n== Early and personal life ==\nBoyce was born in [[Los Angeles, California]], on May 28, 1999.<ref name=\"ABC News\">{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/disney-channel-star-cameron-boyce-dies-20/story?id=64174031|title=Disney Channel Star Cameron Boyce Dies at 20|work=[[ABC News]]|author1=Mark Osborne|author2=Bill Hutchinson|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByBTiPenl9C/|title=Here I am abusing birthday privileges and not placing any value on how many times we revolve around the sun!!!!! Thanks for the birthday wishes, sending love back to everyone sending it to me today \u2764\ufe0f|via=[[Instagram]]|author=Cameron Boyce|date=May 28, 2019|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> His father is of Afro-Caribbean and African-American descent. His mother is Jewish.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VOQi3645_Jc|title=Cameron Boyce Loves Fifth Harmony, Talks Hit Show ''Jessie'' & Looking for a GF!|publisher=PacificRimVideoPress|via=[[YouTube]]|date=April 30, 2014|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rawpages.com/2017/07/cameron-boyce-interview/|title=Cameron Boyce Talks Descendants 2, Biracialism & His Sister's First Boyfriend|publisher=RAW Pages|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> His paternal grandmother, Jo Ann (Allen) Boyce, was one of the [[Clinton High School (Clinton, Tennessee)#Integration|Clinton Twelve]], the first African-Americans to attend an integrated high school in the [[Southern United States]], in 1956, as ordered by ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/human-interest/black-history-month-clinton-12-jo-ann-and-cameron-boyce/|title=Black History Month: Clinton 12, Jo Ann and Cameron Boyce|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Caitlin Keating|date=February 11, 2016|access-date=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBoyce lived in the Los Angeles area with his parents and his younger sister,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/film/actor-cameron-boyce-dies-aged-20-1.883388|title=Actor Cameron Boyce Dies, Aged 20|work=The National|author=Farah Andrews|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> until he moved in with former co-stars [[Karan Brar]] and [[Sophie Reynolds]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BxdJVkVFEFW/|title=Now that we're officially roommates, I am officially Schmidt.|via=[[Instagram]]|author=Cameron Boyce|date=May 14, 2019|access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> He was trained in breakdancing, hip-hop, modern dance, jazz, tap dance, and ballet. His favorite style was breakdancing, and, along with four of his friends, he was a member of the breakdancing crew \"X Mob\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdtvpress.com/disneychannel/bios/letter/B/|title=Bios|publisher=[[Walt Disney Television Press]]|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn May 2008, Boyce made his television debut in the music video \"[[That Green Gentleman (Things Have Changed)]]\", appearing as a younger version of [[Panic! at the Disco]] guitarist [[Ryan Ross]]. In July 2008, he appeared in ''[[General Hospital: Night Shift]]'' as a recurring character named Michael.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C02E3D91638F931A2575BC0A96E9C8B63|title=What's on Tonight?|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Kathryn Shattuck|date=August 12, 2008|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> In August 2008, he made his feature film debut with a starring role in the horror film ''[[Mirrors (film)|Mirrors]]'', as well as appearing in the mystery-thriller film ''[[Eagle Eye]]'' that fall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pegasusnews.com/news/2008/aug/16/movie-review-mirrors/|title=Movie Review: ''Mirrors''|work=[[Pegasus News]]|author=John P. Meyer|date=August 16, 2008|access-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003051512/http://www.pegasusnews.com/news/2008/aug/16/movie-review-mirrors/|archive-date=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/10/02/AR2008100201026.html|title=Family Filmgoer |work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Jane Horwitz|date=October 3, 2008|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Boyce starred as Keith, the spoiled son of [[Adam Sandler]]'s character, in the comedy film ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'' and appeared later that same year showing off his dance skills on the web series ''[[The Legion of Extraordinary Dancers]]''.<ref name=\"TV Guide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/cameron-boyce/credits/295022/|title=Cameron Boyce List of Movies and TV Shows|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Boyce made a guest appearance on [[Disney Channel]]'s [[comedy]] series ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'',<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/obituaries-people-news/cameron-boyce-dead-dies-disney-channel-star-1203260608/|title=Disney Channel Star Cameron Boyce Dies at 20|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Rebecca Rubin|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> and later that month he was one of the featured dancers in a [[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton|royal wedding]] tribute on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2dkl9c|title='Macy's Stars of Dance - Royal Wedding|publisher=Codebear2|via=[[Dailymotion]]|date=December 28, 2014|access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> In June 2011, he had a small role as one of Judy's classmates in the family comedy film ''[[Judy Moody and the Not Bummer Summer]]''.<ref name=\"Variety\" /> In August 2011, he was one of the featured dancers on Disney Channel's comedy series ''[[Shake It Up (American TV series)|Shake It Up]]''.<ref name=\"Variety\" />\n\nIn September 2011, Boyce was cast in the starring role of Luke Ross on Disney Channel's comedy series ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/person/cameron-boyce/credits|title=Cameron Boyce Credits|publisher=[[MovieWeb]]|access-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014031248/http://www.movieweb.com/person/cameron-boyce/credits|archive-date=October 14, 2013}}</ref> During pre-production of the series, the role of Luke was originally intended to be a boy named Hiro adopted from Korea, but casting directors were impressed with Boyce during the audition process and ultimately decided to recreate the role specifically for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newfaces.com/auditions/Television-Commercial-casting-calls_13418|title=Disney's New Show ''Jessie'' Casting Starring Roles|publisher=New Faces|access-date=July 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409094049/http://www.newfaces.com/auditions/Television-Commercial-casting-calls_13418|archive-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GovWKWXKV7E|title=An Exclusive Interview with Cameron Boyce from ''Jessie''|publisher=Pop Culture Passionistas|via=[[YouTube]]|date=September 28, 2011|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Boyce was one of the main cast members in Disney Channel's ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]'', playing Carlos, the son of [[Cruella de Vil]]. He later reprised the character for the animated shorts ''[[Descendants: Wicked World]]'' and in the sequels ''[[Descendants 2]]'' and ''[[Descendants 3]]'', the latter of which was released posthumously.\n\nIn March 2018, Boyce was cast in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] comedy television pilot ''Steps'', in the role of Becker,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/steps-julie-hagerty-cameron-boyce-cast-abc-comedy-pilot-1202350037/|title=''Steps'': Julie Hagerty & Cameron Boyce Cast in ABC Comedy Pilot|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Denise Petski|date=March 20, 2018|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> and was also cast in the indie film ''[[Runt (film)|Runt]]'', in the role of Cal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/descendants-cameron-boyce-runt-indie-movie-1202432194/|title=''Descendants'' Star Cameron Boyce to Topline ''Runt'' Indie Movie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Amanda N'Duka|date=July 23, 2018|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Boyce had joined the cast of [[HBO]]'s ''[[Mrs. Fletcher]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/descendants-cameron-boyce-hbo-comedy-series-mrs-fletcher-kathryn-hahn-1202533977/|title=''Descendants'' Star Cameron Boyce Joins HBO Comedy Series ''Mrs. Fletcher''|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Nellie Andreeva|date=January 17, 2019|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Boyce performed in the music video for \"Almost (Sweet Music)\" by [[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BwFtRKxFonT/|title=@hozier's new video \"Almost (Sweet Music)\" drops April 16th! Big thanks to Andrew and his team for trusting @christinefl0res and I to cook up something cute. Creating for an artist you look up to is a crazy feeling. Thanks for the opportunity @hozier and @_blythethomas !! s/o to @scott.mov you're the bomb.com|via=[[Instagram]]|author=Cameron Boyce|date=April 10, 2019|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> He choreographed the dance with dancer Christine Flores<!-- don't link, as it directs to the wrong person -->, who appeared in the video alongside him.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1148249968836304896|title=Rest well, Cameron. 'Almost (Sweet Music)' by @Hozier \u2013 dance choreographed by Cameron Boyce and Christine Flores.|user=ColumbiaRecords|author=Columbia Records|author-link=Columbia Records|date=July 8, 2019|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> Just prior to his death, Boyce was to begin production with [[Adam Sandler]] on a new project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecameronboycefoundation.org/cameron-boyce-videos-photos|title=About Cameron|work=The Cameron Boyce Foundation|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, it was announced that his clothing line called Archives, co-founded by him and stylist and designer Veronica Graye, would be released in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/thearchivesfrom/|title=Archives from Cameron Boyce|via=[[Instagram]]|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn July 6, 2019, Boyce was found unresponsive at his home address. Authorities were called, and Boyce was pronounced dead at the scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mec.lacounty.gov/2019/press-releases/cause-of-death-cameron-boyce/|title=Cause and Manner of Death Determined for Cameron Boyce|publisher=[[Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner]]|date=July 30, 2019|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a statement made by Boyce's family, Boyce died in his sleep at his home in [[Los Angeles]] \"due to a seizure which was a result of an ongoing medical condition for which he was being treated\".<ref name=\"ABC News\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/dfedb25d661f431880d2044bdcbe25cc|title=Actor Cameron Boyce Dies at Age 20|work=[[Associated Press]]|author=Amy Forliti|date=July 7, 2019 |access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> An autopsy was performed, but release of a cause of death was deferred, until further investigation was done.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2019/07/08/cameron-boyces-cause-death-deferred-pending-further-investigation/1679095001/|title=Disney Star Cameron Boyce's Cause of Death Is Deferred \"Pending Further Investigation\"|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Cydney Henderson|date=July 8, 2019|quote=Public Information Officer Sarah Ardalani said that the actor's cause of death has been deferred \"pending further investigation\" after an autopsy was completed Monday.|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> On July 9, 2019, Boyce's family confirmed that his death was caused by an [[epileptic seizure]] and that Boyce had previously been diagnosed with [[epilepsy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1055609/cameron-boyce-s-family-confirms-he-had-epilepsy-as-they-make-agonizing-funeral-plans|title=Cameron Boyce's Family Confirms He Had Epilepsy as They Make \"Agonizing\" Funeral Plans|work=[[E! News]]|author=McKenna Aiello|date=July 9, 2019|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> The autopsy results were released by the [[Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner]] on July 30, 2019, confirming Boyce's cause of death was due to [[sudden unexpected death in epilepsy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7.com/entertainment/cameron-boyces-death-a-result-of-epilepsy-coroner/5431154/|title=Disney Channel Star Cameron Boyce Suffered 'Sudden Unexpected Death in Epilepsy'|work=[[KABC-TV]]|date=July 30, 2019|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis body was cremated and his ashes returned to the family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/cameron-boyce-was-cremated-death-certificate/|title=Disney Star Cameron Boyce Was Cremated, Death Certificate Reveals|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Natalie Stone|date=July 16, 2019|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy and legacy ==\nIn the span of 40 days in 2017, Boyce helped raise over $27,000 for the [[Thirst Project]], which helps bring clean water to underdeveloped countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/cameron-boyce-descendants-diversity-growing-up|title=Cameron Boyce on ''Descendants'', Diversity in Hollywood, and Growing Up|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|author=Gabe Bergado|date=October 20, 2017|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, Thirst Project officially changed the name of the Pioneering Spirit Award to the Cameron Boyce Pioneering Spirit Award, to honor his work with the organization.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=ThirstProject|title=The Cameron Boyce Pioneering Spirit Award will keep him in our memories forever. It\u2019s an honor to present  @MiniLaddd  with this inaugural award \ud83d\udc99  #ThirstGala\ud83d\udca7 |number=1178176275392782336|date=September 29, 2019|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also supported [[United Way of America]]'s initiative to end homelessness. He helped raise money for the HomeWalk in 2015, and continued to do so up until the end of his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/uzGlgLqwqi/|title=First 5 people to raise $500 or more, will get a PERSONAL SHOUTOUT! Make sure you go to unitedwayla.org/homewalk/ and donate to #TeamCameron thanks guys!!! #Homewalk|via=[[Instagram]]|author=Cameron Boyce|date=October 31, 2014|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, he participated in the opening ceremony of the 12th annual HomeWalk in downtown Los Angeles, one of the largest public events to end homelessness in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laindependent.com/12th-annual-homewalk-raises-1-1-million/|title=12th Annual HomeWalk Raises $1.1 Million|work=The Los Angeles Independent|date=May 23, 2019|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoyce also worked closely with [[It's On Us]], a social movement created to raise awareness and fight against sexual assault on college campuses for both men and women.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bznc88VHi0t/|title=Cameron Boyce was a friend to It's On Us and a strong supporter of the movement to stop campus violence. We are heartbroken to hear he is no longer with us. Sending our love to his family. \u2764\ufe0f|via=[[Instagram]]|author=itsonus|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also worked with the Lucstrong Foundation, which provides grants to families with children who are diagnosed with [[sickle cell disease]] and are going through the [[bone marrow transplant]] process.<ref>{{cite web|author=Boyce Cameron Boyce team|title=Cameron did charity work unfortunately the The Lucstrong Foundation was one very few people knew/know about.. By playing Kick Ball with a bunch of kind hearted people to help a people going through a tough time with Sickle Cell Disease\u2665\ufe0f with is a type of Blood Disorder!|url=https://www.facebook.com/1578999848863505/posts/2397997183630430|via=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis final humanitarian project was called Wielding Peace, a social media campaign in conjunction with Delaney Tarr, co-founder of [[March for Our Lives]]. In Boyce's own words, the campaign would \"help fight against gun violence by showing celebrities and survivors 'wielding' a new kind of weapon \u2014 one of unity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/celebrity/cameron-boyces-loved-ones-plan-to-uphold-his-legacy-by-launching-social-media-campaign/ar-AAE8Egp|title=Cameron Boyce's Loved Ones Plan to \"Uphold His Legacy\" by Launching Social Media Campaign|work=[[MSN]]|author=Jodi Guglielmi|date=July 11, 2019|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== The Cameron Boyce Foundation ===\nThe Cameron Boyce Foundation is a nonprofit organization founded in [[Los Angeles]] that provides young people artistic and creative outlets as alternatives to violence and negativity and uses resources and philanthropy for positive change in the world. The foundation was established in 2019 through [[Network for Good]] to honor Boyce's legacy in the wake of his death,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/10/health/cameron-boyce-death-epilepsy.html|title=How Cameron Boyce's Epilepsy May Have Caused His Death at 20|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Denise Grady|date=July 10, 2019|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> receiving notable support from actors [[Debby Ryan]], [[Karan Brar]] and [[Sophie Reynolds]], among others.\n\nOn July 25, 2019, the foundation disclosed the first project to be carried out was Wielding Peace, which officially launched on August 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0VCC9DAe94/|title=@wieldingpeace\u00a0will be the first funded project by The Cameron Boyce Foundation. Together we will stand to create peace and keep Cameron's legacy alive. Launch date coming soon....|via=[[Instagram]]|author=The Cameron Boyce Foundation|date=July 25, 2019|access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B1MFCZ0gfUZ/|title=@wieldingpeace\u00a0will be the first funded project for The Cameron Boyce Foundation and will launch tomorrow! Please follow\u00a0@wieldingpeace\u00a0and visit our website to learn more about our mission to end gun violence. [...]|via=[[Instagram]]|author=The Cameron Boyce Foundation|date=August 15, 2019|access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> It has involved Brar, Reynolds, and the actor's cousin photographer Taryn Dudley from the beginning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/amp/en-us/2019/08/240159/cameron-boyce-foundation-wielding-peace-limiting-guns|title=Cameron Boyce's Final Project Asks Us to Wield Peace, Not Guns|work=[[Refinery29]]|author=Kaitlin Reilly|date=August 15, 2019|access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the foundation revealed that they donated $8,000 to Thirst Project to build a well in Uganda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3AISAgAHI8/|title=Yesterday, Cameron was honored at the tenth annual Thirst Gala where the award that he received last year was renamed The Cameron Boyce Pioneering Spirit Award. In his speech that he gave just over a year ago, he urged us all to use our resources to help people who need us. We are proud to announce that The Cameron Boyce Foundation has donated $8,000 to Thirst Project to build a well in Uganda. Because of the outpouring of love, and support and generous donations you have given us we are able to carry on the work that Cameron leaves behind. We look forward to continuing to support Thirst Project in their fight to end the global water crisis, and all of the many causes that were important to Cameron. #LiveLikeCameron #LoveLikeCameron#AffectLikeCameron|via=[[Instagram]]|author=The Cameron Boyce Foundation|date=September 29, 2019|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Mirrors (film)|Mirrors]]''\n| Michael Carson\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Eagle Eye]]''\n| Sam Holloman\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]''\n| Keithie Feder\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Game On''\n| Player Two\n| [[Short film]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Judy Moody and the Not Bummer Summer]]''\n| Hunter\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Grown Ups 2]]''\n| Keithie Feder\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Variety\" />\n|-\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| ''[[Runt (film)|Runt]]''\n| Cal\n| Post-production; posthumous release\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Deadline Hollywood\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/cameron-boyce-the-projects-the-young-star-left-behind-descendants-3-mrs-fletcher-runt-paradise-city-1202642708/|title=Cameron Boyce: The Projects the Young Star Left Behind|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Nellie Andreeva|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n<!-- Do NOT add pre-production roles or new unordered TV pilots, as per [[WP:FILMOGRAPHY]] and [[WP:CRYSTAL]] -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[General Hos